{"query": "What are the most effective ways to manage uncropped field margins on European farmland to support bumblebees?", "summary": "The most effective ways to manage uncropped field margins on European farmland to support bumblebees include several approaches based on evidence from European trials. Sowing uncropped arable field margins with agricultural nectar and pollen seed mix has been documented to support foraging bumblebees in five replicated trials in Europe, with four trials showing that field margins sown with perennial leguminous flowering plants attract significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated, grassy or cropped field margins (Action 18). Agricultural forage plant mixes including legumes attract greater numbers of bumblebees than perennial wildflower mixes, at least in the first year, though margins sown with agricultural legume plants degrade in their value to bumblebees and would need re-sowing every few years according to three UK trials (Action 18). 

Sowing uncropped field margins with native wild flower seed mix is also effective, with five replicated UK trials showing that such margins support higher abundance and species richness of foraging bumblebees than cropped field edges, grassy margins or naturally regenerated uncropped margins, with perennial leguminous herbs in seed mixtures being particularly important forage sources for bumblebees, especially long-tongued species (Action 19). Leaving arable field margins uncropped with natural regeneration has shown benefits in four replicated UK trials, with more bumblebees and bee species foraging on uncropped field margins than on cropped margins, though the value is not consistent from year to year and is often based on thistle species considered pernicious weeds (Action 20).

For nesting habitat, increasing areas of rough grassland provides important nesting sites, with one replicated controlled trial in Scotland showing that grassy field margins attracted nest-searching queen bumblebees at higher densities than cropped field margins (Action 12). Providing grass strips at field margins shows mixed results, with some trials showing enhanced abundance and diversity of bumblebees while others showed no effect (Action 14). European agri-environment schemes have shown variable results, with four trials showing enhanced diversity and abundance of wild bees while four other trials found no enhancement (Action 24).", "action_ids": ["18","19","20","12","14","24"]}

