  "relevant_summary": "Based on 14 trials in Europe and North America, phacelia (Phacelia tanacetifolia) shows variable effectiveness as a floral resource for wild bees depending on location. Ten trials (eight replicated) monitored bees foraging on patches sown with a high proportion of phacelia on farmland, and all but one found substantial numbers of foraging wild (non-Apis) bees, particularly bumblebees. Six of these trials recorded the number of foraging bee species, which ranged from eight to 35. However, one replicated trial shows that phacelia is not very attractive to wild bees in Greece, demonstrating clear geographical variation in effectiveness. The evidence indicates that while phacelia generally attracts substantial numbers of wild bees across most European and North American locations studied, its attractiveness varies significantly by region, with notably poor performance documented in Greece compared to other locations.",
  "action_ids": [
    "17"
  ]
}

