{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits of controlling or excluding competitor or predator species from bee nesting sites?",
  "relevant_summary": "The documented benefits of controlling or excluding competitor or predator species from bee nesting sites include increased offspring production. One replicated controlled trial showed that excluding ants from solitary nests of the endemic Australian bee Exonuera nigrescens increased production of offspring (Action 46). Additionally, studies on artificial nest sites show that proper nest design can reduce parasitism and mortality, with nest boxes having plastic-lined holes, plastic or paper tubes being much less productive due to parasitism or mould compared to reed stem and wooden grooved-board nest boxes (Action 47). Mortality rates from parasites and predators in bee nest boxes range from 13% mortality for cavity-nesting bees in Germany to 56% mortality overall for subtropical carpenter bees in India, demonstrating the significant impact that predators and competitors can have on bee reproductive success (Action 47).",
  "action_ids": [
