{
  "query": "What are the documented outcomes and challenges of rearing bumblebees in captivity for reintroduction?",
  "relevant_summary": "Documented outcomes from 22 trials across 13 countries show that captive rearing of bumblebee colonies has been attempted using various methods including confining mated queens alone, with bumblebee workers, honey bee workers, male bumblebee pupae, or following anaesthetisation with CO2 (Action 50). Success rates vary significantly by species, with some North American declining species showing particular challenges - while queens of half-black bumblebee B. vagans and yellow-banded bumblebees B. terricola successfully reared adults in captivity, yellow bumblebee B. fervidus consistently failed as queens laid eggs but larvae died before becoming adults, and similar patterns occurred with rusty-patched bumblebee and American bumblebee B. pensylvanicus (Action 50). One trial documented that over four years of artificial rearing, Bombus terrestris queens gradually decreased in weight (Action 50). Diet composition significantly influences reproductive success, with buff-tailed bumblebee B. terrestris colonies fed freshly frozen pollen producing larger queens with better survival and larger colonies compared to those fed dried, frozen pollen, and workers producing more offspring when fed higher protein content pollen (Action 50). Artificial light regimes of eight hours light and 16 hours darkness can reduce egg-laying time in artificially reared queen B. terrestris relative to constant darkness (Action 50). Hibernation protocols show that queens hibernated at 4-5\u00b0C for 45 days had enhanced egg-laying and colony formation rates but produced smaller colonies than non-hibernated queens, and queens should weigh more than 0.6g and be hibernated for four months or less for good survival (Action 50). For reintroduction, seven replicated trials monitored laboratory-reared colonies introduced to the environment, with variable success - in two UK trials numbers of queens per colony were very low or zero, while two other trials produced good numbers of new queens (Action 52). Social parasitism by cuckoo bees presents a significant challenge, with rates varying from 0% in five trials to 25-66% and 79% in others, though parasitism was reduced by placing colonies in landscapes with intermediate nectar and pollen availability and releasing later in the season (Action 52). Supplementary feeding effects are inconsistent, with one Canadian trial showing improved reproductive success but no reduction in parasite load, while a USA trial found no increase in colony productivity (Action 52). Translocation trials from the 1950s-1960s showed evidence of queen death and lower colony productivity, with only early bumblebee Bombus pratorum colonies adapting well to being moved (Action 53).",
  "action_ids": [
    "50",
    "52",
    "53"
  ]
}

