{
  "action_id": "54",
  "action_title": "Rear and manage populations of solitary bees",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\nSeveral species of solitary bee in the family Megachilidae are reared and managed commercially as pollinators, mostly for the forage crop alfalfa, or fruit trees.\u00a0These species readily nest in drilled wooden blocks, or stacked grooved boards of wood or polystyrene. Parasites and pathogens can be problematic and a number of control methods have been developed. Rearing methods have been investigated for two other species not yet commercially managed and one replicated trial shows that temperature regimes are important to survival. If rearing for conservation purposes is to be attempted, we would recommend a systematic review of these methods.\nThree management trials with megachilids not commercially managed in the USA or Poland, and a review of studies of managed species, found that local populations can increase up to six-fold in one year under management if conditions are good and plentiful floral resources are provided.\nTwo replicated trials have reared solitary bees on artificial diets. One found high larval mortality in Osmia cornuta reared on artificial pollen-based diets, including honey bee-collected pollen. The other found Megachile rotundata could be reared on an artificial diet based on honey bee-collected pollen, but bees reared on synthetic pollen substitutes either died or had low pre-pupal weight."
}

{
  "query": "What is the evidence for the effectiveness of different sown floral mixes on agricultural land for wild bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Evidence for the effectiveness of different sown floral mixes on agricultural land for wild bees shows varied outcomes depending on mix composition and bee species. Five replicated trials in Europe documented bumblebees foraging on field margins sown with agricultural nectar and pollen seed mixes, with four trials showing that margins sown with perennial leguminous flowering plants attracted significantly more foraging bumblebees than naturally regenerated, grassy, or cropped field margins (Action 18). Three replicated trials demonstrated that agricultural forage plant mixes including legumes attracted greater numbers of bumblebees than perennial wildflower mixes, at least in the first year (Action 18). However, three UK trials found that margins sown with agricultural legume plants degraded in value to bumblebees and would need re-sowing every few years (Action 18). Fourteen trials in Europe and North America recorded substantial numbers of wild bees foraging on perennial or annual sown flowering plants in agricultural environments (Action 17). Ten trials monitoring bees foraging on patches with high proportions of phacelia found substantial numbers of foraging wild bees, particularly bumblebees, with species counts ranging from eight to 35 (Action 17). Five replicated UK trials showed that uncropped field margins sown with wild flowers supported higher abundance and species richness of foraging bumblebees than cropped field edges, grassy margins, or naturally regenerated margins (Action 19). Two trials demonstrated that perennial leguminous herbs in seed mixtures were important forage sources for bumblebees, particularly long-tongued species (Action 19). One replicated trial showed long-tongued bumblebee species strongly preferred perennial wildflower seed mix over annual forage plant mixes (Action 19). One large trial showed positive correlation between long-tongued bumblebee abundance and the number of pollen and nectar agri-environment agreements (Action 362). However, evidence for solitary bees remains limited, with no evidence captured on field margin management effects for this group (Actions 18, 19).",
