{
  "query": "What factors are known to influence the occupancy and productivity of artificial nest sites provided for solitary bees?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several factors influence the occupancy and productivity of artificial nest sites for solitary bees. Distance from foraging resources is critical - nest boxes must be placed within 150-600 m of forage resources based on replicated experiments estimating the foraging range of four medium to large European solitary bee species (Action 47). Nest box design and materials significantly affect productivity - reed stem and wooden grooved-board nest boxes produced more bees per nest than other types, while nest boxes with plastic-lined holes, plastic or paper tubes were much less productive due to parasitism or mould (Action 47). Occupancy rates varied from 1-26% of available cavities in studies (Action 80). Twenty-three replicated trials showed cut hollow stems or tubes being occupied by solitary bees, while eleven trials demonstrated occupation of drilled wooden blocks (Action 47). Parasitism and predation significantly impact productivity - mortality rates range from 13% for cavity-nesting bees and wasps in Germany to 56% overall mortality for subtropical carpenter bees in India (Action 47). Temperature regimes are important for survival in rearing conditions (Action 54). Ant exclusion can increase offspring production, as demonstrated in one controlled trial with Australian bee Exonurea nigrescens (Action 46). Multiple years of nest box provision can increase occupancy - the number of occupied solitary bee nests almost doubled over three years in Germany (Actions 47, 80). Some sites showed population increases over time, with one study finding estimated foraging bee numbers increased in fields with nest boxes compared to fields without boxes (Action 47).",
