{
  "query": "What factors, such as diet and social parasitism, have been shown to affect the success of captive-rearing and reintroducing bumblebee colonies?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several factors have been shown to affect the success of captive-rearing and reintroducing bumblebee colonies based on experimental evidence. Diet composition significantly influences reproductive success in captive-reared bumblebees, with three replicated trials demonstrating that pollen diet affects reproductive outcomes (Action 50). Buff-tailed bumblebee colonies fed on freshly frozen pollen produced larger queens that survived better and produced larger colonies themselves compared to colonies fed on dried, frozen pollen, and workers can produce more offspring when fed pollen with higher protein content (Action 50). Social parasitism by cuckoo bees represents a major challenge, with variable rates of parasitism observed in reintroduced colonies ranging from zero to 79% across different trials (Action 52). Parasitism rates were reduced by placing colonies in landscapes with intermediate rather than very high nectar and pollen availability and releasing them late rather than early in the season (Action 52). Supplementary feeding showed mixed results, with one Canadian trial finding it improved reproductive success of captive-reared colonies but did not reduce parasite load, while a USA trial found no increase in colony productivity (Action 52). Artificial hibernation regimes affect colony establishment, with hibernation at 4-5\u00b0C for 45 days enhancing egg-laying and colony formation rates, though hibernated queens produced smaller colonies than non-hibernated queens (Action 50). Queens should weigh more than 0.6 g and be hibernated for four months or less for good survival chances (Action 50). Light regimes also influence development, with eight hours light and 16 hours darkness reducing the time for artificially reared queens to lay eggs compared to constant darkness (Action 50). Additionally, translocation can negatively impact colonies, with evidence showing queen death and lower colony productivity following movement (Action 53).",
